WEBVTT

00:04.059 --> 00:06.497
(DRUMROLL)

00:08.398 --> 00:10.968
(FANFARE PLAYING)

00:12.000 --> 00:18.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

00:23.313 --> 00:24.748
(MUSIC ENDS)

00:27.754 --> 00:32.753
Subtitles by explosiveskull

00:32.756 --> 00:36.493
(EXPLOSIONS)

00:46.837 --> 00:50.407
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

01:02.819 --> 01:05.486
BOY: "You are about to meet
a strange people

01:05.488 --> 01:08.456
"in a strange enemy country.

01:08.458 --> 01:10.893
"You must keep clear
of the Germans.

01:10.895 --> 01:12.063
"You must not...

01:13.530 --> 01:17.031
(SLOWLY)
"...fraternize."

01:17.033 --> 01:18.367
What does that mean?

01:18.369 --> 01:20.438
It means we shouldn't be
friendly to them.

01:31.280 --> 01:32.749
(SIGHS)

01:56.874 --> 01:59.711
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

02:03.346 --> 02:06.818
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

02:13.990 --> 02:15.790
This house is requisitioned
for British use

02:15.792 --> 02:17.961
by order of
the Control Commission, Germany.

02:21.664 --> 02:23.533
You'll forgive us, <i>Fraulein.</i>

02:24.734 --> 02:26.902
WILKINS: It belongs
to a family Lubert.

02:26.904 --> 02:28.972
He's an architect, sir.

02:41.619 --> 02:43.454
(BRAKES SCREECHING)

02:44.989 --> 02:45.987
(KNOCK AT DOOR)

02:45.989 --> 02:47.488
CONDUCTOR: All change.

02:47.490 --> 02:49.725
(TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING)

02:49.727 --> 02:53.798
(INDISTINCT ANNOUNCEMENT
ON PA)

03:01.906 --> 03:03.338
WOMAN:
He's meeting you here, is he?

03:03.340 --> 03:04.876
BURNHAM: Susan.

03:06.843 --> 03:08.243
- BURNHAM: How was your trip?
- SUSAN: Long.

03:08.245 --> 03:09.177
Quick, let's get home.

03:09.179 --> 03:11.081
(CHUCKLES)

03:19.356 --> 03:20.657
Rachael.

03:21.825 --> 03:23.090
Hello, Lewis.

03:23.092 --> 03:24.095
My God. Look at you.

03:25.295 --> 03:26.531
It's freezing.

03:27.329 --> 03:28.432
It is.

03:29.733 --> 03:30.668
Here.

03:31.636 --> 03:33.704
Let me take this.

03:37.507 --> 03:40.912
(ANNOUNCER SPEAKING
IN GERMAN ON RADIO)

03:45.514 --> 03:47.416
Welcome. Please come inside.

03:47.418 --> 03:49.718
Let me show you the house.

03:49.720 --> 03:52.789
Please, come inside.
Let me show you the house.

04:06.502 --> 04:09.639
(CHIMING IN DISTANCE)

04:24.554 --> 04:26.090
LEWIS:
They're still finding bodies.

04:27.157 --> 04:30.494
There's over 25,000 dead
still unaccounted for.

04:33.631 --> 04:35.230
How are you?

04:35.232 --> 04:37.801
Good. Fine. You?

04:39.402 --> 04:41.035
It's...

04:41.037 --> 04:42.138
It's been difficult.

04:43.140 --> 04:44.675
For you, too, I expect.

04:45.241 --> 04:46.576
For all of us.

04:48.145 --> 04:50.612
We dropped more bombs
on Hamburg in one weekend

04:50.614 --> 04:52.717
than fell on London
in the whole of the war.

04:55.552 --> 04:57.220
That's different.

05:00.056 --> 05:01.592
Yeah.

05:40.631 --> 05:42.667
LEWIS: Thank you, Barker.

05:45.501 --> 05:46.669
Colonel Morgan.

05:46.671 --> 05:48.737
- Welcome.
- <i>Herr</i> Lubert.

05:48.739 --> 05:51.306
Please come inside.
Let me show you the house.

05:51.308 --> 05:53.077
This is my wife, Mrs. Morgan.

05:54.277 --> 05:55.646
LUBERT: How do you do?

05:57.748 --> 05:59.984
- After you, Mrs. Morgan.
- Thank you.

06:07.758 --> 06:09.693
The finest room of the house.

06:10.527 --> 06:12.063
It's lovely,
isn't it, darling?

06:14.030 --> 06:15.265
RACHAEL:
It's very modern.

06:16.232 --> 06:17.367
LUBERT: Yes, it is.

06:21.739 --> 06:23.771
That's a Steinway.

06:23.773 --> 06:26.009
- An excellent instrument.
- Yes.

06:27.011 --> 06:27.943
Do you play?

06:27.945 --> 06:29.778
Actually,
I've rather let it slip.

06:29.780 --> 06:32.183
LUBERT: Well, it will be good
to have it played again.

06:33.984 --> 06:35.753
What was up there before?

06:37.054 --> 06:39.955
LUBERT: A painting.
It was damaged.

06:39.957 --> 06:41.392
I haven't replaced it yet.

06:42.359 --> 06:45.196
So the main staircase is
this way.

06:52.169 --> 06:53.535
Our library.

06:53.537 --> 06:55.136
LEWIS:
Herr Lubert's an architect.

06:55.138 --> 06:56.405
LUBERT: Was.

06:56.407 --> 06:58.309
Now I'm a metal press operator.

07:00.344 --> 07:01.812
Shall we?

07:06.282 --> 07:07.848
LUBERT: <i>Die Elbe.</i>

07:07.850 --> 07:10.085
It flows all the way
to the, uh...

07:10.087 --> 07:11.752
I'm sorry,
I don't have the English.

07:11.754 --> 07:13.121
The <i>Deutsche See?</i>

07:13.123 --> 07:15.622
- North Sea.
- The North Sea, yes.

07:15.624 --> 07:17.261
It's all the same sea
in the end.

07:18.227 --> 07:19.263
LUBERT: Indeed.

07:20.597 --> 07:22.233
It's cold.
Can we go in?

07:30.707 --> 07:32.743
I hope you can be
as happy here as we were.

07:34.111 --> 07:35.876
My daughter and I
will stay out of your way

07:35.878 --> 07:37.748
until we move to the camp.

07:39.549 --> 07:40.885
Thank you.

07:57.534 --> 08:00.271
RACHAEL (MUFFLED): You should
have told me, that's all.

08:21.325 --> 08:22.760
RACHAEL:
What?

08:25.095 --> 08:26.897
Thinking of our honeymoon.

08:37.440 --> 08:38.909
My God.

08:41.777 --> 08:43.179
You look beautiful.

08:47.017 --> 08:48.451
You've still got this.

08:49.753 --> 08:50.988
Of course.

08:58.329 --> 08:59.229
(SIGHS SOFTLY)

09:06.736 --> 09:08.104
You're smoking?

09:11.542 --> 09:15.144
Dr. Mayfield said that it
would help with my nerves.

09:15.146 --> 09:16.280
And has it?

09:42.638 --> 09:44.508
The cabin, you remember?

09:45.709 --> 09:47.311
With its leaky roof.

09:51.915 --> 09:54.351
- It rained for two weeks.
- It did.

09:56.885 --> 09:58.752
And, my God, that cold.

09:58.754 --> 10:00.121
You burnt my books.

10:00.123 --> 10:01.756
Well, I had to.
I had no choice.

10:01.758 --> 10:03.224
It was Agatha Christie.

10:03.226 --> 10:05.361
You might have waited
until I found out who did it.

10:06.430 --> 10:08.663
- The butler.
- The butler always did it.

10:08.665 --> 10:10.067
LEWIS:
Mm-hmm.

10:12.603 --> 10:14.071
Happy times.

10:21.678 --> 10:23.277
(CAR DOOR CLOSES)

10:23.279 --> 10:24.581
(ENGINE STARTS)

10:36.893 --> 10:39.263
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

10:43.066 --> 10:45.002
WILKINS: Good.
The governor's here.

10:46.470 --> 10:48.169
LEWIS: Wilkins.

10:48.171 --> 10:49.371
Sir.

10:49.373 --> 10:51.472
They were hit delivering
food to the camp, sir.

10:51.474 --> 10:52.808
A grenade, I believe.

10:52.810 --> 10:53.940
Two of ours dead.

10:53.942 --> 10:55.910
Bloody looters
are making it worse.

10:55.912 --> 10:57.645
BURNHAM: Back!
Get them back!

10:57.647 --> 10:59.514
- BURNHAM: Push them back!
- POLICE: Come on, move.

10:59.516 --> 11:01.382
- (CROWD CLAMORING)
- SOLDIER: Get them off!

11:01.384 --> 11:02.183
BURNHAM: Christ.

11:02.185 --> 11:03.984
The breath on these people.

11:03.986 --> 11:04.987
Yes, well, that's what

11:04.989 --> 11:07.054
900 calories a day
does to you.

11:07.056 --> 11:08.625
Well, at least they're less
trouble when they're hungry.

11:09.959 --> 11:13.063
Keith Burnham,
Divisional Intelligence.

11:15.065 --> 11:16.667
So what have we got?

11:18.201 --> 11:19.833
- Is that him?
- WILKINS: That's the fella.

11:19.835 --> 11:23.905
Looks like Werwolves. 88s.

11:23.907 --> 11:25.841
Nazi bastards
who won't accept we've won.

11:25.843 --> 11:27.876
LEWIS: Captain, can we have
these two boys taken care of?

11:27.878 --> 11:29.444
WILKINS: Absolutely.

11:29.446 --> 11:31.846
(YELLS IN GERMAN)

11:31.848 --> 11:33.584
- (GUNSHOT)
- (PEOPLE SCREAM)

11:34.984 --> 11:36.785
LEWIS: A medic!
Wilkins, get a medic.

11:36.787 --> 11:38.088
WILKINS: Yes, sir!

11:40.290 --> 11:42.660
(CHOKING)

11:47.062 --> 11:48.932
BURNHAM: Thought so. 88.

11:51.935 --> 11:54.338
(MUTTERS)
<i>Heil Hitler.</i>

11:55.604 --> 11:58.374
BURNHAM: Private.
Get our men on the truck.

11:59.710 --> 12:01.311
And somebody bag this one up.

12:37.614 --> 12:39.182
(SIGHS)

13:00.336 --> 13:03.072
Oh. Hello.

13:04.541 --> 13:05.542
You must be Freda.

13:07.810 --> 13:09.313
What were you reading?

13:16.787 --> 13:17.687
LUBERT: Freda.

13:18.689 --> 13:21.025
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

13:27.330 --> 13:29.130
(IN ENGLISH)
She never listens.

13:29.132 --> 13:31.035
I'm only her father.

13:31.801 --> 13:32.770
(CHUCKLES)

13:34.870 --> 13:37.306
(LUBERT SPEAKING GERMAN)

13:52.622 --> 13:54.058
(HEIKE SPEAKING GERMAN)

14:04.868 --> 14:06.637
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

14:08.071 --> 14:09.572
I'm sorry, I... I don't...

14:11.307 --> 14:13.710
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

14:32.628 --> 14:34.398
(DOOR OPENS)

14:35.532 --> 14:36.767
(DOOR CLOSES)

14:38.634 --> 14:40.436
Sorry, emergency.

14:42.171 --> 14:44.472
(CONVERSING IN GERMAN)

14:44.474 --> 14:46.841
Ooh, I see you have coffee.

14:46.843 --> 14:47.942
Yeah, I'd... I'd prefer tea.

14:47.944 --> 14:49.678
They don't really do tea.

14:49.680 --> 14:51.978
I'll rustle some up
from the NAAFI.

14:51.980 --> 14:54.216
- Coffee it is, then.
- No.

14:54.218 --> 14:55.619
Sleep well?

14:56.585 --> 14:57.753
Actually, I did.

14:58.653 --> 14:59.789
Good.

15:01.224 --> 15:02.655
That's really good.

15:02.657 --> 15:05.229
I'm looking forward
to it being just us.

15:07.930 --> 15:09.163
What?

15:09.165 --> 15:10.400
Uh...

15:11.701 --> 15:12.635
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

15:16.439 --> 15:18.342
What if we let them
stay on?

15:19.441 --> 15:21.275
The staff? Do we need them?

15:21.277 --> 15:22.613
The Luberts.

15:24.013 --> 15:26.180
So you mean...
Live with them?

15:26.182 --> 15:28.549
I mean, they'd be
on the top floor.

15:28.551 --> 15:30.320
Rach, we'd hardly notice
they're here.

15:31.387 --> 15:33.588
- Is everyone doing it?
- Here.

15:33.590 --> 15:35.658
It's not the same. No one else
has a house like this.

15:36.859 --> 15:38.193
This isn't what we wanted.

15:38.195 --> 15:42.163
The big house, the staff,
the art on the walls.

15:42.165 --> 15:43.800
I know.

15:44.768 --> 15:46.266
I thought we were going
to be together.

15:46.268 --> 15:47.568
We are together.

15:47.570 --> 15:48.672
Alone.

15:51.807 --> 15:52.875
I...

15:54.877 --> 15:56.513
I'm not comfortable with it.

15:58.681 --> 16:00.948
With them.
Not comfortable with them

16:00.950 --> 16:01.951
because they're Germans.

16:08.557 --> 16:10.359
It's chaos out there, Rachael.

16:11.527 --> 16:12.926
There's nowhere to put
these people.

16:12.928 --> 16:13.995
There's nowhere to...

16:13.997 --> 16:15.195
Nothing to feed these people.

16:15.197 --> 16:16.896
There's...

16:16.898 --> 16:18.632
(SIGHS)

16:18.634 --> 16:21.301
It does... It makes no sense
to throw the Luberts out.

16:21.303 --> 16:23.706
You didn't tell me
what I was walking into.

16:25.207 --> 16:26.507
This isn't how
it was supposed to be.

16:26.509 --> 16:28.742
None of this is how
it is supposed to be.

16:28.744 --> 16:29.845
And yet here we are.

16:40.356 --> 16:42.323
(INDISTINCT)

16:42.325 --> 16:43.560
Thank you.

16:44.527 --> 16:46.562
- I'm very grateful.
- You're very welcome.

16:47.564 --> 16:48.632
Thank you.

16:49.965 --> 16:51.198
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

16:51.200 --> 16:52.400
(HEIKE GRUNTS)

16:52.402 --> 16:54.871
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

17:12.454 --> 17:14.320
Sorry. Uh...
Could, um...

17:14.323 --> 17:16.290
Could one of you
help me, please?

17:16.291 --> 17:17.461
I want to move the plants.

17:20.630 --> 17:21.763
The plants?

17:22.665 --> 17:24.599
They're blocking the light.

17:35.244 --> 17:36.913
(CONVERSING IN GERMAN)

17:41.384 --> 17:44.788
(LAUGHTER IN DISTANCE)

18:18.620 --> 18:20.489
You don't like the chair?

18:25.395 --> 18:26.663
It's a Mies van der Rohe.

18:28.097 --> 18:29.998
"The house
of construction."

18:30.000 --> 18:32.032
It's meant to be one of
the most comfortable chairs

18:32.034 --> 18:33.201
ever invented.

18:33.203 --> 18:35.168
Well, it isn't.

18:35.170 --> 18:36.340
It's ugly.

18:37.506 --> 18:39.740
He was of the Bauhaus school.

18:39.742 --> 18:41.642
Their philosophy was
all about rejecting

18:41.644 --> 18:42.777
unnecessary adornment.

18:42.779 --> 18:44.378
Do you really need
a philosophy

18:44.380 --> 18:45.881
to make something
comfortable?

18:47.149 --> 18:50.184
Well, behind every object,
there is a philosophy,

18:50.186 --> 18:51.919
isn't there?

18:51.921 --> 18:54.890
<i>Herr</i> Lubert, please don't
creep about the house.

18:56.158 --> 18:58.628
I thought we agreed
to keep to our own quarters.

18:59.661 --> 19:01.864
Our "zones."
Yes, of course.

19:02.932 --> 19:04.197
I will try to remember.

19:04.199 --> 19:07.402
And if your daughter
wants anything from her room,

19:07.404 --> 19:08.839
I'll get Heike
to bring it up to her.

19:10.106 --> 19:11.505
This is all very new to her.

19:11.507 --> 19:12.775
All the same.

19:15.543 --> 19:17.779
- I will make words with her.
- Have words.

19:17.781 --> 19:19.547
- Sorry?
- In English, you don't

19:19.549 --> 19:21.752
"make" words with someone.

19:26.388 --> 19:28.356
- LUBERT: You should have these.
- (KEYS JANGLING)

19:28.358 --> 19:30.659
As the lady of the house.

19:51.914 --> 19:54.618
Delicious, Heike.
<i>Danke schon,</i> really.

19:59.321 --> 20:01.056
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

20:03.225 --> 20:04.895
<i>Danke, Frau</i> Morgan.

20:06.462 --> 20:07.731
(CHUCKLES)

20:10.465 --> 20:13.466
Look, she's doing it again.
She's smirking.

20:13.468 --> 20:16.138
Because you said
she was delicious.

20:18.373 --> 20:19.906
(LAUGHS)

20:19.908 --> 20:22.579
- I was making an effort.
- I know.

20:25.380 --> 20:27.647
(CASE OPENS AND CLOSES)

20:27.649 --> 20:29.619
I don't know
how you do it.

20:30.485 --> 20:31.921
What?

20:33.156 --> 20:37.124
You go on like before,
all your little rituals.

20:37.126 --> 20:38.795
Get up, shave.

20:40.362 --> 20:42.599
Have a meal, go to work.

20:43.599 --> 20:45.968
- Like nothing had changed.
- Please, Rachael.

20:47.703 --> 20:49.739
I don't think it's healthy
to talk this way.

20:51.006 --> 20:52.007
- No?
- No.

20:53.242 --> 20:54.975
Oh.

20:54.977 --> 20:57.278
No? How... How am I expected
to talk?

20:57.280 --> 20:59.049
You might like
to set an example.

21:04.786 --> 21:07.223
When did you get to be
so self-righteous?

21:17.867 --> 21:19.002
(SIGHS)

21:19.801 --> 21:21.204
(DOOR SLAMS IN DISTANCE)

22:00.109 --> 22:02.311
(RACHAEL SOBBING)

22:19.929 --> 22:21.095
(CAR HONKS)

22:21.097 --> 22:22.898
(PEOPLE SPEAKING GERMAN)

22:25.068 --> 22:26.735
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

22:34.043 --> 22:35.210
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

22:36.612 --> 22:37.813
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

22:40.949 --> 22:43.319
SUSAN: Come on.
Let's have that tea.

22:44.320 --> 22:47.621
I don't know when he got
to be so sanctimonious.

22:47.623 --> 22:50.059
You stifle under the weight
of all that decency.

22:51.060 --> 22:53.964
Lawrence of Hamburg,
Keith calls him.

22:54.964 --> 22:57.731
The one who went queer
for the natives.

22:57.733 --> 22:59.633
He actually seems
to like Lubert.

22:59.635 --> 23:01.204
Lew let them stay on.

23:03.740 --> 23:04.941
Is that wise?

23:05.908 --> 23:07.841
There may not be
an outward show of hatred,

23:07.843 --> 23:09.778
but it's there
below the surface.

23:10.745 --> 23:13.015
Be careful, that's all.
They're not like us.

23:24.593 --> 23:26.228
Good afternoon.

23:31.667 --> 23:34.337
(PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

24:02.231 --> 24:03.431
Freda.

24:03.433 --> 24:04.968
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

24:13.542 --> 24:15.108
It's fine.

24:15.110 --> 24:16.710
Please forgive her,
Mrs. Morgan.

24:16.712 --> 24:18.378
She should have asked
permission.

24:18.380 --> 24:20.848
- It's all right.
- It's not.

24:20.850 --> 24:22.683
- She plays well.
- She plays very badly.

24:22.685 --> 24:23.951
She never practices.

24:23.953 --> 24:25.618
Claudia despaired of her.

24:25.620 --> 24:26.889
Claudia?

24:27.756 --> 24:29.024
Her mother.

24:29.725 --> 24:31.191
My wife.

24:31.193 --> 24:32.091
Oh.

24:32.093 --> 24:34.129
Is she somewhere
in the house too?

24:35.598 --> 24:37.200
She died in the firestorm.

24:42.138 --> 24:43.706
I'm so sorry.

24:47.976 --> 24:49.041
Um...

24:49.043 --> 24:52.780
If Freda wants to play,
I don't see why not.

24:52.782 --> 24:54.313
In the afternoons,
for half an hour or so, I...

24:54.315 --> 24:56.852
I thought we agreed
to keep to our "zones."

25:14.270 --> 25:15.371
(DOOR CLOSES)

25:25.814 --> 25:28.150
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

25:52.175 --> 25:55.341
(SHOUTING IN GERMAN IN DISTANCE)

25:55.343 --> 25:57.312
- (SLAM IN DISTANCE)
- (SHOUTING CONTINUES)

26:16.564 --> 26:19.434
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

26:24.740 --> 26:27.844
(DRIVER SPEAKING GERMAN)

26:30.044 --> 26:31.678
(GIRL SPEAKING GERMAN)

26:31.680 --> 26:32.913
CAPTAIN: You'll be paid
in food vouchers

26:32.915 --> 26:34.248
- for your work, given a meal...
- WOMAN: Freda.

26:34.250 --> 26:35.782
...and brought
back home before dark.

26:35.784 --> 26:37.550
Are you 16?

26:37.552 --> 26:39.354
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

26:42.858 --> 26:44.260
(AX THUDDING)

27:23.965 --> 27:27.236
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

27:29.871 --> 27:31.407
SOLDIER: Bodies!

27:32.375 --> 27:33.376
Bodies here!

27:37.714 --> 27:39.413
CAPTAIN:
All right, stand back.

27:39.415 --> 27:40.848
SOLDIER: Get them away
from it, Tom, will you?

27:40.850 --> 27:42.148
SOLDIER 2:
Not a bad way to go...

27:42.150 --> 27:43.916
One last screw
before lights out.

27:43.918 --> 27:45.385
(SOLDIERS LAUGH)

27:45.387 --> 27:47.052
- Come.
- CAPTAIN: Back to work, you lot.

27:47.054 --> 27:48.355
(ALBERT SPEAKING GERMAN)

27:48.357 --> 27:50.026
CAPTAIN:
Bag up these bones.

27:58.100 --> 28:00.469
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

28:32.134 --> 28:34.201
LUBERT:
Forgive me for intruding.

28:34.203 --> 28:36.803
It's freezing upstairs.
I cut some firewood earlier.

28:36.805 --> 28:38.539
- Do you mind if I...
- No, not at all.

28:38.541 --> 28:39.943
No need to ask permission.

28:41.343 --> 28:42.675
We're going out this evening,

28:42.677 --> 28:43.612
but can I get you a drink?

28:44.647 --> 28:45.982
LUBERT:
No, thank you.

28:48.783 --> 28:52.051
Well then. Good night.

28:52.053 --> 28:53.255
LEWIS: Good night.

29:06.769 --> 29:09.672
(JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING
ON PHONOGRAPH)

29:10.973 --> 29:13.276
- LEWIS: Still got it.
- Keith won't be long.

29:15.211 --> 29:17.211
- We're so glad you could come.
- Thank you.

29:17.213 --> 29:19.146
Well, it's good
to finally meet you

29:19.148 --> 29:22.048
and a relief to be
out of the house.

29:22.050 --> 29:23.884
What a house, though.

29:23.886 --> 29:25.455
It's almost worth
living with a German.

29:27.455 --> 29:28.454
It's so funny.

29:28.456 --> 29:30.824
You've got one, too.
A missing painting.

29:30.826 --> 29:32.459
We have one just like it.

29:32.461 --> 29:33.460
Everyone does.

29:33.462 --> 29:35.361
It's where
they would have hung him.

29:35.363 --> 29:36.530
Who?

29:36.532 --> 29:38.199
The <i>Fuhrer.</i>

29:38.201 --> 29:39.566
"The stain
that can't be removed."

29:39.568 --> 29:42.235
They're usually clever enough
to cover them up.

29:42.237 --> 29:43.270
Hmm.

29:43.272 --> 29:45.308
BURNHAM:
Sorry to keep you. Apologies.

29:46.774 --> 29:48.308
Thank you.

29:48.310 --> 29:50.176
BURNHAM: Based on their answers,
we assign them a category

29:50.178 --> 29:51.645
from black to white.

29:51.647 --> 29:52.913
They're clean,

29:52.915 --> 29:54.947
they get their <i>Persilschein,</i>

29:54.949 --> 29:56.983
their laundry ticket.

29:56.985 --> 29:58.452
It's the certificate

29:58.454 --> 30:00.354
allowing them to return
to a normal life.

30:00.356 --> 30:03.424
Does Lubert have
his <i>Persilschein?</i>

30:03.426 --> 30:04.527
Does it matter?

30:05.426 --> 30:06.192
Yes.

30:06.194 --> 30:07.860
I think I have the right

30:07.862 --> 30:09.194
to know if I'm living
with a Nazi.

30:09.196 --> 30:10.431
Yes, I think it does matter.

30:10.433 --> 30:11.998
I don't think
you can judge a person

30:12.000 --> 30:14.267
by his answers
to a questionnaire.

30:14.269 --> 30:16.569
No? How do you judge him?

30:16.571 --> 30:18.073
You look him in the eye.

30:19.475 --> 30:21.942
- Lubert was never in uniform.
- That's not the point.

30:21.944 --> 30:23.475
Well, there was no blood
on his hands.

30:23.477 --> 30:25.311
SUSAN: There's blood
on all their hands.

30:25.313 --> 30:28.115
RACHAEL: Honestly, Lew,
I sometimes wonder whose side you're on.

30:28.117 --> 30:30.183
Even after everything
that they've done...

30:30.185 --> 30:31.686
LEWIS: The war is over.
We won.

30:33.054 --> 30:34.456
That's the end of it.

30:42.330 --> 30:43.930
Let's have dessert
in the drawing room.

30:43.932 --> 30:45.668
Well, does he or not?

30:46.801 --> 30:48.569
Not yet.

30:48.571 --> 30:49.738
It's a formality.

30:50.973 --> 30:52.175
SUSAN: Shall we?

30:53.042 --> 30:57.346
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

31:01.382 --> 31:02.751
SOLDIER:
Morning, sir.

31:09.858 --> 31:11.293
SOLDIER:
Papers, ma'am.

31:13.994 --> 31:15.330
Papers.

31:16.631 --> 31:17.831
There you are.

31:17.833 --> 31:19.134
Papers, sir.

32:10.151 --> 32:11.821
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

32:23.098 --> 32:26.301
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

32:33.641 --> 32:36.511
So you were building houses
for Nazi officials.

32:37.846 --> 32:41.284
After 1933, we built
what we were told to build.

32:47.956 --> 32:49.188
DONNELL:
Did the bombing affect

32:49.190 --> 32:51.193
the health of you
and your family?

32:53.395 --> 32:55.464
It's a simple question.

32:57.331 --> 32:59.401
It affected the health
of my wife.

33:01.235 --> 33:02.836
She was one
of the 40,000 killed

33:02.838 --> 33:05.273
when British bombers
razed this city to the ground.

33:07.208 --> 33:10.076
July 27th, 1943.

33:10.078 --> 33:11.881
Well, let's talk
about your wife.

33:13.048 --> 33:14.180
The money was hers?

33:14.182 --> 33:16.649
Her family was wealthy, yes.

33:16.651 --> 33:18.418
They owned a number
of shipping yards.

33:18.420 --> 33:21.922
Shipping yards used
to transfer Nazi weapons?

33:21.924 --> 33:23.522
LUBERT:
Among many other things.

33:23.524 --> 33:25.325
You have to understand
that my wife and I

33:25.327 --> 33:27.527
had nothing to do
with her family business.

33:27.529 --> 33:31.463
Yet you claim to never
have joined the Nazi Party?

33:31.465 --> 33:35.003
I was against everything
the Nazis stood for.

33:36.538 --> 33:38.241
That wasn't my question.

33:40.975 --> 33:41.977
No.

33:42.977 --> 33:44.613
I was never a party member.

33:55.189 --> 33:57.459
BURNHAM: Did you know
about the camps?

33:59.160 --> 34:00.395
No.

34:01.663 --> 34:03.796
So you've never seen these?

34:03.798 --> 34:05.034
Here.

34:07.035 --> 34:08.370
Have a look.

34:19.281 --> 34:20.813
DONNELL:
One last question.

34:20.815 --> 34:23.583
During the war, did you ever
hope for a German victory?

34:23.585 --> 34:26.418
You answered,
"I wanted it to end."

34:26.420 --> 34:28.288
I wanted to go back
to how it was.

34:28.290 --> 34:31.060
What, you miss the past?
Is that it?

34:33.395 --> 34:34.830
I miss my wife.

34:40.134 --> 34:41.467
BURNHAM:
All right.

34:41.469 --> 34:43.438
You'll hear from us
in due course.

35:00.221 --> 35:01.487
(DOOR OPENS)

35:01.489 --> 35:02.792
<i>Herr</i> Lubert?

35:04.192 --> 35:05.391
(DOOR CLOSES)

35:05.393 --> 35:07.293
<i>Herr</i> Lubert?

35:07.295 --> 35:08.663
Could you come
in here, please?

35:16.304 --> 35:17.773
Could you explain this?

35:22.578 --> 35:24.411
It's a von Guerard.

35:24.413 --> 35:25.512
I'm not asking what it is.

35:25.514 --> 35:26.980
I'm asking
what it's doing here.

35:26.982 --> 35:30.217
You objected to the stain,
so I covered it.

35:30.219 --> 35:31.617
What's the matter,
don't you like it?

35:31.619 --> 35:33.485
That's not the point.
What's it covering?

35:33.487 --> 35:34.887
Does it offend you?

35:34.889 --> 35:36.690
He was German,
maybe that offends you.

35:36.692 --> 35:38.828
It was a picture of him,
wasn't it?

35:39.594 --> 35:41.831
- Of him?
- Your <i>Fuhrer.</i>

35:46.101 --> 35:47.069
It's simple for you.

35:48.103 --> 35:49.335
The war ends.

35:49.337 --> 35:50.906
You go home the winner.

35:51.739 --> 35:54.507
- Your conscience is clear.
- Oh.

35:54.509 --> 35:56.708
Is your conscience
not clear?

35:56.710 --> 35:58.779
I thought you would like
the painting.

35:58.781 --> 36:01.380
I apologize if I was mistaken.

36:01.382 --> 36:03.085
Would you object
to a landscape?

36:04.219 --> 36:05.719
A nice hunting scene perhaps?

36:05.721 --> 36:08.255
- I object to your tone.
- (SHOUTS) Then throw us out!

36:08.257 --> 36:10.056
- <i>Herr</i> Lubert.
- Throw us out.

36:10.058 --> 36:11.659
You hate us.

36:12.627 --> 36:14.059
It's what you want.

36:14.061 --> 36:15.862
- Throw us out.
- Nobody said anything about...

36:15.864 --> 36:17.663
We can leave you alone
to fight with your husband,

36:17.665 --> 36:19.435
when he bothers to be here.

36:24.038 --> 36:25.137
I think you've said enough.

36:25.139 --> 36:26.542
Then throw us out.

36:27.308 --> 36:29.011
Here. I'll give you a reason.

36:39.119 --> 36:40.522
I think you should go.

37:11.552 --> 37:13.755
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

37:26.467 --> 37:27.735
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

37:33.442 --> 37:34.777
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

37:37.444 --> 37:39.214
(CHILDREN CHATTERING)

37:42.583 --> 37:44.752
(ALBERT SPEAKING GERMAN)

38:22.357 --> 38:23.659
(CHILD GIGGLES)

38:56.290 --> 38:58.157
(FREDA SPEAKING GERMAN)

38:58.159 --> 38:59.828
(ALBERT SPEAKING GERMAN)

39:05.532 --> 39:08.670
(INHALES)

39:58.719 --> 40:01.122
(VEHICLE APPROACHES)

40:03.692 --> 40:06.728
(MUSIC PLAYING ON RECORD)

40:18.172 --> 40:19.273
What do you think?

40:22.076 --> 40:24.710
- It's stunning.
- (CHUCKLES) Idiot.

40:24.712 --> 40:26.681
- LEWIS: Me?
- I meant the table.

40:27.815 --> 40:32.087
Burnham at the head
or next to Susan?

40:34.089 --> 40:36.755
Let's just keep him
away from the alcohol.

40:36.757 --> 40:38.724
Just don't argue with him.

40:38.726 --> 40:40.592
- Mm-hmm.
- Be English.

40:40.594 --> 40:42.397
Talk about the weather.

40:43.732 --> 40:44.864
What are you doing?

40:44.866 --> 40:48.067
I was just admiring
your dress.

40:48.069 --> 40:49.902
Oh.

40:49.904 --> 40:52.137
- Thinking how lucky I am.
- (RACHAEL CHUCKLES)

40:52.139 --> 40:53.773
Do you like it?

40:53.775 --> 40:55.911
You ought to,
it took me long enough.

40:57.645 --> 40:58.980
I'm imagining...

41:00.614 --> 41:02.317
what you look like out of it.

41:07.121 --> 41:09.521
(TELEPHONE RINGS IN DISTANCE)

41:09.523 --> 41:11.590
When do our guests arrive?

41:11.592 --> 41:12.958
Not for an hour.

41:12.960 --> 41:15.161
- Not for an hour.
- Uh-uh.

41:15.163 --> 41:16.462
Hmm.

41:16.464 --> 41:18.396
You are...

41:18.398 --> 41:20.768
(GRETA SPEAKING GERMAN)

41:26.741 --> 41:28.243
Go upstairs.

41:37.118 --> 41:38.486
(DOOR OPENS)

41:41.188 --> 41:42.491
Lock the door.

41:45.460 --> 41:46.525
What is it?

41:46.527 --> 41:48.964
There's a protest
at headquarters.

41:50.831 --> 41:52.632
I'm sorry, my love, but...

41:52.634 --> 41:56.438
Well, you'll have to entertain
the guests until I get back.

42:05.413 --> 42:06.813
Go on, then.

42:06.815 --> 42:08.350
Go and save Germany.

42:10.851 --> 42:12.453
Don't be like that.

42:15.857 --> 42:17.893
I'll be back as soon as I can.

42:20.295 --> 42:21.293
(DOOR OPENS)

42:21.295 --> 42:22.431
Wish me luck.

42:24.199 --> 42:25.367
(DOOR CLOSES)

42:27.768 --> 42:30.003
(ALL SHOUTING)

42:30.005 --> 42:32.975
ALL (CHANTING):
Feed us! Feed us! Feed us!

42:35.377 --> 42:36.275
LEWIS: Captain.

42:36.277 --> 42:37.777
They've barricaded
the street, sir.

42:37.779 --> 42:39.145
They're not letting
anybody in or out.

42:39.147 --> 42:40.579
LEWIS: I want
this street closed off.

42:40.581 --> 42:42.882
Captain, tell the men
there is to be no firing.

42:42.884 --> 42:45.117
(SHOUTING CONTINUES)

42:45.119 --> 42:46.619
SOLDIER:
Break through!

42:46.621 --> 42:48.090
SOLDIER 2:
We need more men!

42:54.663 --> 42:56.563
- SOLDIER: Get back!
- (WOMAN SCREAMS)

42:56.565 --> 42:57.963
(WOMAN GROANING)

42:57.965 --> 43:00.034
Hey! Hey, hey!

43:01.936 --> 43:03.538
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

43:05.772 --> 43:07.907
- SOLDIER: Back!
- (LUBERT GRUNTS)

43:07.909 --> 43:10.476
(CROWD CONTINUES CHANTING)

43:10.478 --> 43:13.579
- Sir. Sir, where are you going?
- (TIRES SQUEALING)

43:13.581 --> 43:15.050
Get back!

43:24.125 --> 43:25.360
(GROANS)

43:29.330 --> 43:30.398
(GUNSHOT)

43:32.567 --> 43:35.270
LEWIS:
No firing. No firing!

43:39.775 --> 43:42.608
(MUFFLED CHATTER)

43:42.610 --> 43:45.011
- It's outrageous. A clergyman?
- A chance to rebuild.

43:45.013 --> 43:46.380
THOMPSON:
What choice have we got?

43:48.382 --> 43:49.882
Thank you, Heike.

43:49.884 --> 43:52.319
We've done them a favor.
Now it's time to leave.

43:52.321 --> 43:55.023
We're talking about war.
Nobody really wins, do they?

43:55.956 --> 43:57.422
ELIOT: There's nothing
left for us here.

43:57.424 --> 43:59.759
French got the wine.
Yanks got the view.

43:59.761 --> 44:00.994
What, we got the ruins?

44:00.996 --> 44:02.261
(SOFT CHUCKLE)

44:02.263 --> 44:04.333
And what does
<i>Herr</i> Lubert think?

44:07.268 --> 44:09.103
I don't know.
You'd have to ask him.

44:11.440 --> 44:13.773
Well, I must say,
this is good hock.

44:13.775 --> 44:15.577
Thank <i>Herr</i> Lubert.

44:28.389 --> 44:29.655
ALL:
<i>♪ With many cheerful facts ♪</i>

44:29.657 --> 44:31.960
<i>♪ About the square
of the hypotenuse ♪</i>

44:33.795 --> 44:36.862
<i>♪ I'm very good at integral
and differential calculus ♪</i>

44:36.864 --> 44:38.197
<i>♪ I know
the scientific names... ♪</i>

44:38.199 --> 44:41.235
(CONVERSING IN GERMAN)

44:42.302 --> 44:44.137
<i>♪ ...of a modern Major-General ♪</i>

44:44.139 --> 44:46.139
- (CHEERING)
- Bravo!

44:46.141 --> 44:47.542
(SPEAKING IN GERMAN)

44:49.576 --> 44:50.876
Oh!

44:50.878 --> 44:53.112
<i>Herr</i> Lubert! Come and join us.

44:53.114 --> 44:55.951
My husband wants
your opinion on something.

45:01.556 --> 45:03.855
I'm not feeling my best.

45:03.857 --> 45:05.993
But thank you all the same.

45:08.029 --> 45:09.561
Good night.

45:09.563 --> 45:11.197
(SINGING)
<i>♪ If you don't thrill me ♪</i>

45:11.199 --> 45:12.965
<i>♪ Like you used to thrill me ♪</i>

45:12.967 --> 45:14.335
<i>♪ That's sabotage ♪</i>

45:15.770 --> 45:18.603
<i>♪ If you don't kiss me
like you used to kiss me ♪</i>

45:18.605 --> 45:20.674
<i>♪ That's sabotage ♪</i>

45:20.676 --> 45:23.041
I would ask you not to hit
the piano like that.

45:23.043 --> 45:24.210
<i>♪ When you hear
sirens screamin' ♪</i>

45:24.212 --> 45:26.045
<i>♪ Those be-alert alarms ♪</i>

45:26.047 --> 45:27.179
It belonged to my wife.

45:27.181 --> 45:30.282
<i>♪ Don't run helter-skelter ♪</i>

45:30.284 --> 45:33.619
<i>♪ There's a bomb-proof shelter
in my arms ♪</i>

45:33.621 --> 45:34.920
- (POUNDING KEYS)
- Lubert.

45:34.922 --> 45:36.558
Lubert, Lubert...

45:37.891 --> 45:39.560
Steady on.
All right, all right.

45:44.398 --> 45:45.730
Sorry about the glass,
old boy.

45:45.732 --> 45:47.635
Stefan.

46:03.851 --> 46:05.150
MAN: Well done.

46:05.152 --> 46:06.751
I'm so sorry.

46:06.753 --> 46:07.755
What for?

46:09.223 --> 46:11.192
I'm the one
who should apologize.

46:16.364 --> 46:17.598
Good night.

46:19.900 --> 46:21.136
Good night.

46:23.270 --> 46:24.339
(SIGHS)

46:39.020 --> 46:40.455
That's not necessary.

46:41.589 --> 46:43.324
You've got grit in it.

46:52.232 --> 46:54.101
This is going to hurt.

46:57.038 --> 46:58.407
(GRUNTS SOFTLY)

47:05.346 --> 47:07.482
You've been avoiding me.

47:09.417 --> 47:10.518
Have I?

47:11.786 --> 47:13.088
I don't think so.

47:14.688 --> 47:16.290
I was going to apologize.

47:18.025 --> 47:19.394
For what?

47:23.998 --> 47:25.400
Don't.

47:27.302 --> 47:28.703
I was going to...

47:29.938 --> 47:31.239
but I won't.

47:37.043 --> 47:38.413
Rachael.

48:26.927 --> 48:28.330
(BOTH GROAN)

48:42.009 --> 48:44.578
(CAR APPROACHING)

48:48.715 --> 48:49.817
Stop.

48:58.627 --> 48:59.728
(DOOR OPENS)

49:08.835 --> 49:10.272
Everything all right?

49:11.672 --> 49:12.940
Uh...

49:14.442 --> 49:16.409
What happened to you?

49:16.411 --> 49:18.313
I was caught up in a protest.

49:19.346 --> 49:21.045
LEWIS:
You were at the protest?

49:21.047 --> 49:23.047
LUBERT:
Not by choice.

49:23.049 --> 49:24.983
Then you know what happened.

49:24.985 --> 49:26.353
Bloody people tried
to kill me.

49:27.654 --> 49:29.654
I mean, what is the matter
with this country?

49:29.656 --> 49:31.725
You don't realize
we're here to help?

49:32.927 --> 49:33.962
I should go.

49:37.165 --> 49:39.400
- Good night.
- LEWIS: Good night.

49:41.034 --> 49:43.538
I'm sorry. How was the party?

49:44.605 --> 49:45.807
Fine.

49:46.975 --> 49:48.174
I'm tired.
I'm going to go up.

49:48.176 --> 49:50.411
All right.
I'll be up in a bit.

49:55.748 --> 49:57.319
(SIGHS)

50:21.842 --> 50:22.877
(DOOR OPENS)

50:30.918 --> 50:32.817
Ah. Freda.

50:32.819 --> 50:37.822
Listen, do you have
something of mine? Yes?

50:37.824 --> 50:40.291
My wife gave it to me.
There are photographs in there,

50:40.293 --> 50:41.830
and I would like it back.

50:43.230 --> 50:44.766
Perhaps you've seen it?

50:48.435 --> 50:49.937
- Freda, I...
- (HISSES)

50:59.913 --> 51:01.549
(ENGINE STARTS)

51:10.857 --> 51:12.526
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

51:36.049 --> 51:37.985
- Morning.
- Morning, sir.

51:39.052 --> 51:40.788
- Sir.
- LEWIS: Thank you.

51:43.723 --> 51:44.792
Sir.

51:47.293 --> 51:48.763
There's been an attack.

51:50.531 --> 51:52.264
Bomb, sir.
In the Russian zone.

51:52.266 --> 51:53.768
LEWIS: Oh, Christ.

51:54.969 --> 51:56.902
It's only for a few days.

51:56.904 --> 51:58.637
I'll be back in time
for Christmas.

51:58.639 --> 52:02.308
Well, where are you going?
I could come with you.

52:02.310 --> 52:03.645
I'm sorry, no.

52:07.415 --> 52:09.081
"This is the army,
Mrs. Jones."

52:09.083 --> 52:10.183
LEWIS: Yes.

52:10.185 --> 52:13.420
I'll make it up to you,
I promise. Hmm?

52:17.192 --> 52:18.893
I suppose
I should be used to it.

52:24.397 --> 52:25.966
Six days.

52:27.735 --> 52:28.803
Sorry?

52:30.237 --> 52:31.473
I asked.

52:33.139 --> 52:34.576
I checked.

52:37.244 --> 52:39.445
They'd have given you
six days leave

52:39.447 --> 52:40.915
after the funeral...

52:45.219 --> 52:46.621
and you didn't take it.

52:51.592 --> 52:52.927
Why didn't you take it?

52:56.563 --> 52:57.762
I asked myself that

52:57.764 --> 52:59.331
and I had a lot of time
to think about it.

52:59.333 --> 53:01.168
- Please.
- And then I thought, why...

53:03.371 --> 53:07.273
"Maybe he just doesn't...

53:07.275 --> 53:09.541
- Rach.
- "...feel it like I do."

53:09.543 --> 53:11.078
(SHATTERING)

53:14.047 --> 53:16.514
- He wasn't there.
- No.

53:16.516 --> 53:18.550
There was a war on.
I had a job to do.

53:18.552 --> 53:19.821
What did I have?

53:24.991 --> 53:26.060
Nothing.

53:27.360 --> 53:28.862
(SIGHS)

53:30.764 --> 53:32.567
What is it you want from me?

53:35.402 --> 53:36.604
Lewis...

53:42.076 --> 53:43.778
I want him back.

53:52.585 --> 53:54.087
I can't do that for you.

53:56.089 --> 53:58.489
Lewis. Lewis. Please.

53:58.491 --> 54:00.227
I'm asking you.
I'm begging you.

54:02.563 --> 54:04.065
Please don't go.

54:08.502 --> 54:09.871
I'm going out.

54:11.304 --> 54:12.773
(SIGHS)

54:16.210 --> 54:17.545
(SNIFFLES)

54:19.647 --> 54:20.949
(DOOR CLOSES)

54:23.583 --> 54:26.821
(ARIA PLAYING ON PHONOGRAPH)

55:07.527 --> 55:10.764
(ARIA CONTINUES)

55:50.571 --> 55:52.139
- Sir.
- Barker.

56:00.980 --> 56:04.718
(LEWIS AND BARKER
CONVERSING INDISTINCTLY)

56:06.587 --> 56:08.255
(ENGINE STARTS)

56:56.770 --> 56:59.436
(BIRDS TWITTERING)

56:59.438 --> 57:01.743
(TWITTERING CONTINUES)

59:40.467 --> 59:42.036
- (MUSIC STOPS)
- (CHUCKLES)

59:44.036 --> 59:46.439
Michael could never manage
that bit, either.

59:49.308 --> 59:50.511
Michael.

59:52.612 --> 59:54.048
My son.

59:57.717 --> 59:59.386
He died in the war.

01:00:03.322 --> 01:00:07.962
A bomb hit our house
on July the 2nd, 1942...

01:00:09.630 --> 01:00:11.065
and killed him.

01:00:14.768 --> 01:00:16.404
He was 11.

01:00:20.708 --> 01:00:22.877
He'd be about your age
right now.

01:00:26.647 --> 01:00:28.947
He used to come home
from school.

01:00:28.949 --> 01:00:30.551
He'd have...

01:00:31.951 --> 01:00:34.054
He'd have ink
all over his hands.

01:00:36.690 --> 01:00:38.492
I'd have to spend hours...

01:00:41.194 --> 01:00:43.263
He'd get it all over the keys.

01:00:47.801 --> 01:00:49.103
And I don't...

01:00:50.103 --> 01:00:52.005
I don't think I can,
um...

01:00:55.609 --> 01:00:57.545
I don't know if I can,
um...

01:00:59.580 --> 01:01:01.148
I don't...
(SNIFFLES)

01:01:03.884 --> 01:01:05.552
...think I can cope.

01:01:08.288 --> 01:01:09.657
Because...

01:01:11.859 --> 01:01:14.261
I should have stopped him.
I should have...

01:01:16.864 --> 01:01:18.532
I was his mother.

01:01:21.601 --> 01:01:23.436
I was his mother.

01:01:28.375 --> 01:01:29.944
I can't...

01:01:32.411 --> 01:01:33.580
I can't...

01:01:34.748 --> 01:01:36.083
I couldn't...

01:01:36.850 --> 01:01:38.616
- I can't bear it.
- Freda.

01:01:38.618 --> 01:01:40.921
I can't bear
(SOBBING)

01:01:42.889 --> 01:01:44.425
I can't...

01:01:46.627 --> 01:01:48.462
I can't bear it.

01:01:50.130 --> 01:01:51.598
LUBERT (WHISPERING):
It's all right.

01:01:55.768 --> 01:01:57.337
(SHUSHES SOFTLY)

01:02:01.040 --> 01:02:02.542
RACHAEL:
I can't.

01:02:19.360 --> 01:02:21.159
(KNOCK AT DOOR)

01:02:21.161 --> 01:02:22.495
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

01:02:24.799 --> 01:02:26.100
Mrs. Morgan.

01:02:31.772 --> 01:02:34.375
I wondered if you'd like
to join me for breakfast.

01:02:36.710 --> 01:02:38.279
Both of you.

01:02:41.748 --> 01:02:43.049
We would like that very much.

01:02:54.627 --> 01:02:57.895
I have somebody coming over
tomorrow to do my hair,

01:02:57.897 --> 01:03:00.367
if Freda would like
to join me.

01:03:02.868 --> 01:03:04.237
Freedie?

01:03:06.773 --> 01:03:09.409
- Thank you, Mrs. Morgan.
- FREDA: Why?

01:03:10.743 --> 01:03:12.345
What's wrong with my hair?

01:03:27.293 --> 01:03:29.730
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

01:03:33.900 --> 01:03:36.203
(PROJECTOR WHIRRING)

01:03:40.607 --> 01:03:42.143
(ALL CHUCKLE)

01:03:54.186 --> 01:03:55.954
(LUBERT SPEAKING GERMAN)

01:03:55.956 --> 01:03:57.588
(FREDA SPEAKING GERMAN)

01:03:57.590 --> 01:03:58.759
(DOOR CLOSES)

01:04:01.761 --> 01:04:04.064
(PROJECTOR STOPS)

01:04:19.011 --> 01:04:20.878
(KNOCK AT DOOR)

01:04:20.880 --> 01:04:22.480
Come in.

01:04:22.482 --> 01:04:25.416
<i>Herr</i> Lubert. <i>Frau</i> Morgan.

01:04:25.418 --> 01:04:27.384
Will you need me
this afternoon?

01:04:27.386 --> 01:04:30.457
No, thank you, Greta.
That will be all.

01:04:44.071 --> 01:04:45.572
(DOOR OPENS)

01:06:32.179 --> 01:06:33.881
(RACHAEL MOANING)

01:06:52.199 --> 01:06:53.998
(DOGS BARKING)

01:06:54.000 --> 01:06:56.536
(GUARD SPEAKING RUSSIAN)

01:07:01.174 --> 01:07:02.842
KUTOV:
These were your men.

01:07:07.581 --> 01:07:09.483
LEWIS: Do you have
the man responsible?

01:07:10.382 --> 01:07:11.851
I'd like to see him.

01:07:19.426 --> 01:07:23.864
KUTOV: Siegfried Leitman,
former SS <i>Sturmbannfuhrer.</i>

01:07:29.335 --> 01:07:30.934
(LEWIS SPEAKING GERMAN)

01:07:30.936 --> 01:07:32.772
- Yes, I do.
- Good.

01:07:36.875 --> 01:07:38.976
This boy.

01:07:38.978 --> 01:07:40.547
Do you know him?

01:07:41.315 --> 01:07:42.850
- No.
- Come on.

01:07:46.585 --> 01:07:48.887
Come on.
You wear the same mark.

01:07:48.889 --> 01:07:51.422
There are many of us
with that mark.

01:07:51.424 --> 01:07:52.791
Then give me their names.

01:07:52.793 --> 01:07:54.395
Why would I do that?

01:07:57.031 --> 01:07:59.632
Colonel, this man
still has his bootlaces on.

01:08:00.801 --> 01:08:02.400
KUTOV: An oversight.

01:08:02.402 --> 01:08:04.038
He might have hanged himself.

01:08:05.639 --> 01:08:08.572
But you didn't, did you?
Because you're a coward.

01:08:08.574 --> 01:08:11.444
And you send children
to do your killing.

01:08:12.344 --> 01:08:15.081
Yes. They make
the best killers.

01:08:16.049 --> 01:08:17.814
They don't question it.

01:08:17.817 --> 01:08:20.216
And you don't have the stomach
for handling them.

01:08:20.219 --> 01:08:21.586
That's where you're wrong.

01:08:21.587 --> 01:08:23.921
See, I killed
younger than this.

01:08:23.923 --> 01:08:26.256
When the war was on, before
the bureaucrats took over,

01:08:26.258 --> 01:08:27.756
I killed every German
I got my hands on.

01:08:27.759 --> 01:08:29.926
- Yes.
- Because I wanted it to end.

01:08:29.928 --> 01:08:32.162
You are murderers too.

01:08:32.163 --> 01:08:34.332
You think we have forgotten?

01:08:34.334 --> 01:08:36.667
You are like a child
who covers his eyes

01:08:36.669 --> 01:08:38.135
and thinks
the world goes away.

01:08:38.136 --> 01:08:40.005
But we won't forget.

01:08:40.006 --> 01:08:43.573
We will cut your men's throats
in the streets.

01:08:43.576 --> 01:08:45.609
We will burn your women
in their homes.

01:08:45.611 --> 01:08:46.711
We will bomb your children

01:08:46.712 --> 01:08:49.116
while they are sleeping
in their beds.

01:08:50.249 --> 01:08:52.247
KUTOV: Colonel Morgan.

01:08:52.250 --> 01:08:54.053
- You want it?
- <i>Nein!</i>

01:08:55.721 --> 01:09:00.426
- Now, give me their names.
- (LEITMAN COUGHING)

01:09:32.424 --> 01:09:34.426
(RACHAEL LAUGHS)

01:09:35.995 --> 01:09:37.563
I'm so sorry.

01:09:38.432 --> 01:09:40.501
No.
(SCREAMS)

01:09:47.538 --> 01:09:49.109
We're nearly there.

01:09:51.877 --> 01:09:53.913
(BOTH LAUGHING)

01:10:03.289 --> 01:10:05.122
RACHAEL:
It's still freezing.

01:10:05.124 --> 01:10:07.925
I actually can't feel my toes.

01:10:07.927 --> 01:10:10.063
Oh, that's not good.
Let me check.

01:10:11.697 --> 01:10:13.297
What are you doing?

01:10:13.299 --> 01:10:14.931
- I'm just checking.
- Stop it.

01:10:14.933 --> 01:10:17.135
- Stop it. (LAUGHING)
- Yep, still here.

01:10:17.137 --> 01:10:18.403
So are your feet.

01:10:18.405 --> 01:10:21.072
- Stop it.
- Ankles, yep. Calves.

01:10:21.074 --> 01:10:22.643
And your thighs.

01:10:29.415 --> 01:10:30.482
Before the war,

01:10:30.484 --> 01:10:32.186
I bought some land
in the Alps.

01:10:33.285 --> 01:10:34.721
Near Oberstdorf.

01:10:35.621 --> 01:10:38.989
It's not much now,
just a cabin,

01:10:38.991 --> 01:10:40.123
a bit like this one.

01:10:40.125 --> 01:10:41.561
Warmer, I hope.

01:10:42.794 --> 01:10:44.764
I'm going to build a house.

01:10:46.298 --> 01:10:47.868
Something very modern.

01:10:49.937 --> 01:10:51.138
Just one floor...

01:10:52.271 --> 01:10:53.974
set into the hillside...

01:10:55.340 --> 01:10:57.641
with steel beams
and a glass wall

01:10:57.643 --> 01:10:59.713
facing the beautiful
pine trees.

01:11:02.348 --> 01:11:04.083
You can ski to the front door.

01:11:07.954 --> 01:11:09.722
What do you think?

01:11:10.490 --> 01:11:11.925
Could you live in it?

01:11:14.593 --> 01:11:15.928
I don't know how to ski.

01:11:16.896 --> 01:11:17.997
(BOTH LAUGH)

01:11:19.231 --> 01:11:20.998
You're smiling.

01:11:21.000 --> 01:11:23.203
- I smile all the time.
- Hardly ever.

01:11:24.236 --> 01:11:25.806
Not since you came here.

01:11:27.472 --> 01:11:28.774
I like you like this.

01:11:33.279 --> 01:11:36.215
I never thought that I could be
happy like this again.

01:11:37.718 --> 01:11:39.186
Then come with us.

01:11:41.553 --> 01:11:44.087
You don't have your papers.

01:11:44.089 --> 01:11:45.258
How will you travel?

01:11:46.258 --> 01:11:47.694
They will clear me.

01:11:48.761 --> 01:11:50.731
It's just a matter of time.

01:12:07.146 --> 01:12:09.650
This is <i>Stunde Null.</i>

01:12:10.417 --> 01:12:11.985
The Zero Hour.

01:12:14.219 --> 01:12:15.989
Everything can start again.

01:12:39.277 --> 01:12:40.914
(FREDA SPEAKING GERMAN)

01:12:57.597 --> 01:12:59.299
(SPEAKING GERMAN)

01:13:53.686 --> 01:13:55.155
(SIGHS)

01:13:59.092 --> 01:14:01.895
I let him get to me. Leitman.

01:14:02.896 --> 01:14:04.761
I shouldn't have.

01:14:04.763 --> 01:14:07.297
- He murdered children, sir.
- Hmm.

01:14:07.299 --> 01:14:09.770
If it was me,
I would have loaded the gun.

01:14:11.937 --> 01:14:14.003
You would have loaded
the gun?

01:14:14.005 --> 01:14:15.073
Yeah.

01:14:15.075 --> 01:14:16.207
(BOTH LAUGH)

01:14:16.209 --> 01:14:17.144
No, you wouldn't have.

01:14:18.377 --> 01:14:19.879
Yeah. No, I wouldn't.

01:14:20.946 --> 01:14:23.213
Dad always said I lack
the spine to be a soldier.

01:14:23.215 --> 01:14:25.483
Yes.

01:14:25.485 --> 01:14:28.355
Then I think your dad
probably gave you a compliment.

01:14:32.725 --> 01:14:35.094
It's not the war
that makes men of us.

01:14:39.831 --> 01:14:42.302
I've done things
I'm certainly not proud of.

01:14:45.672 --> 01:14:47.240
I often wonder, my wife...

01:14:48.106 --> 01:14:52.712
if she knew...
how she'd feel about me.

01:15:02.955 --> 01:15:05.756
Let's get out of this
bloody cold and go home.

01:15:05.758 --> 01:15:07.260
(ENGINE STARTS)

01:15:08.393 --> 01:15:11.798
(WOMAN TALKING INDISTINCTLY)

01:15:12.999 --> 01:15:15.402
(GIRL SQUEALING, GIGGLING)

01:15:24.276 --> 01:15:26.512
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

01:15:32.584 --> 01:15:35.521
(SINGING INDISTINCTLY)

01:15:57.276 --> 01:15:58.344
SUSAN:
Rachael.

01:16:00.480 --> 01:16:01.481
Sorry I'm late.

01:16:02.447 --> 01:16:03.881
Now, what's all this about?

01:16:03.883 --> 01:16:06.050
RACHAEL:
I need a favor.

01:16:06.052 --> 01:16:08.155
It's taking a long time
to clear Lubert.

01:16:09.355 --> 01:16:11.121
What's your secret?

01:16:11.123 --> 01:16:12.890
- What?
- Something's changed.

01:16:12.892 --> 01:16:15.458
Oh, it's my hair.
I had it done.

01:16:15.460 --> 01:16:17.129
No. Mmm.

01:16:18.298 --> 01:16:19.833
Something else.

01:16:22.334 --> 01:16:23.536
It's Christmas.

01:16:24.770 --> 01:16:26.138
I've always liked Christmas.

01:16:27.138 --> 01:16:28.275
Really?

01:16:29.375 --> 01:16:30.576
I can't stand it.

01:16:31.611 --> 01:16:33.280
Not Christmas
without children.

01:16:38.852 --> 01:16:40.554
Oh, is the teddy bear
for the girl?

01:16:42.422 --> 01:16:44.290
- Yes.
- And...

01:16:45.624 --> 01:16:47.058
The cigars?

01:16:47.060 --> 01:16:49.025
- For my husband.
- When he gets back?

01:16:49.027 --> 01:16:51.865
Yes. For when he gets back.

01:16:56.201 --> 01:16:57.868
Well, I suppose
I could ask Keith

01:16:57.870 --> 01:17:00.239
what's taking so long
to clear him.

01:17:15.387 --> 01:17:17.556
(PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

01:17:55.960 --> 01:17:57.828
If you're going
to spy on a girl,

01:17:57.830 --> 01:18:00.564
the least you could do
is pay her a compliment.

01:18:00.566 --> 01:18:01.799
Hello, Rach.

01:18:01.801 --> 01:18:03.634
- (MUSIC STOPS)
- LEWIS: I'm home.

01:18:03.636 --> 01:18:04.905
Lewis.

01:18:12.044 --> 01:18:13.545
Is Lubert around?

01:18:15.246 --> 01:18:16.712
Uh...

01:18:16.714 --> 01:18:18.248
I think he's in the garden.

01:18:18.250 --> 01:18:20.583
- Why?
- He should join us.

01:18:20.585 --> 01:18:23.589
I'm going to clean up.
I have some news.

01:18:28.428 --> 01:18:29.493
(CORK POPS)

01:18:29.495 --> 01:18:30.597
Oh.

01:18:33.065 --> 01:18:35.265
What are we celebrating?

01:18:35.267 --> 01:18:37.337
I've been offered a new post.

01:18:38.905 --> 01:18:40.240
Ah.

01:18:41.206 --> 01:18:43.075
Your trip was successful?

01:18:43.875 --> 01:18:46.045
Successful? Well, um...

01:18:46.945 --> 01:18:48.578
Let us see, shall we?

01:18:48.580 --> 01:18:50.715
<i>Herr</i> Morgan?
Shall I prepare supper?

01:18:50.717 --> 01:18:52.015
That won't
be necessary, Greta.

01:18:52.017 --> 01:18:54.551
We're going out to
a regimental dinner tonight.

01:18:54.553 --> 01:18:57.688
But you can please join us
for a glass of champagne.

01:18:57.690 --> 01:18:59.292
Come on. Come in and join us.

01:19:00.759 --> 01:19:02.091
A second Christmas.

01:19:02.093 --> 01:19:04.627
Shall we say a Russian one.

01:19:04.629 --> 01:19:06.598
A post? Where?

01:19:07.834 --> 01:19:09.302
The War Office.

01:19:09.901 --> 01:19:11.404
London.

01:19:12.771 --> 01:19:14.206
We're going home.

01:19:15.674 --> 01:19:16.676
So?

01:19:18.477 --> 01:19:19.643
I've been cleared.

01:19:19.645 --> 01:19:21.244
(LAUGHS)
I knew it.

01:19:21.246 --> 01:19:24.116
Congratulations. Burnham
must have pulled some strings.

01:19:25.451 --> 01:19:27.385
- That's really wonderful.
- LEWIS: Yes, it is.

01:19:27.387 --> 01:19:29.953
RACHAEL:
I, um... I don't understand.

01:19:29.955 --> 01:19:31.555
You haven't finished
your work here.

01:19:31.557 --> 01:19:33.457
Well, I put in a request.
I didn't want to tell you.

01:19:33.459 --> 01:19:34.791
I didn't want you
to get your hopes up.

01:19:34.793 --> 01:19:36.426
But we're going home.

01:19:36.428 --> 01:19:38.128
Hmm?

01:19:38.130 --> 01:19:40.764
So, from both of us,
I'd like to say thank you,

01:19:40.766 --> 01:19:44.170
and to new beginnings.

01:20:00.084 --> 01:20:02.121
(INDISTINCT SHOUTING)

01:20:05.624 --> 01:20:07.527
Bertie?

01:20:11.297 --> 01:20:12.365
Bertie?

01:20:35.687 --> 01:20:36.688
Bertie.

01:20:45.597 --> 01:20:47.801
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

01:21:09.120 --> 01:21:10.355
Right.

01:21:12.557 --> 01:21:13.659
Sorry.

01:21:15.060 --> 01:21:16.763
This dress, it isn't right.

01:21:27.307 --> 01:21:29.172
(WHISPERING) What are you doing?
He's downstairs.

01:21:29.174 --> 01:21:30.576
Just tell him.

01:21:32.111 --> 01:21:34.411
Tell him you're leaving
with me tonight.

01:21:34.413 --> 01:21:36.449
- I can't.
- Then I will.

01:21:43.856 --> 01:21:45.792
No, it has to come from me.

01:21:56.968 --> 01:21:58.737
- LEWIS: It's the same dress.
- What?

01:21:59.739 --> 01:22:00.807
Oh.

01:22:02.441 --> 01:22:03.676
Yes.

01:22:19.857 --> 01:22:21.293
My love.

01:22:22.962 --> 01:22:24.795
Sir.

01:22:24.797 --> 01:22:27.232
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

01:22:34.139 --> 01:22:35.642
SUSAN: Rachael!

01:22:38.343 --> 01:22:40.579
- Lew.
- Yes?

01:22:42.280 --> 01:22:43.747
We need to talk.

01:22:43.749 --> 01:22:44.884
Colonel.

01:22:47.652 --> 01:22:49.923
Just a minute.

01:22:54.861 --> 01:22:56.394
- LEWIS: General.
- How are you?

01:22:56.396 --> 01:22:57.994
LEWIS: Good, good.
How are you?

01:22:57.996 --> 01:22:59.499
(DOOR CLOSES)

01:23:03.502 --> 01:23:04.637
(SIGHS)

01:23:20.652 --> 01:23:23.253
BROOK: You know
you'll be wasted in Whitehall.

01:23:23.255 --> 01:23:24.453
Well, you're leaving this city

01:23:24.455 --> 01:23:25.891
in better shape
than you found it.

01:23:26.859 --> 01:23:28.257
Cheers.

01:23:28.259 --> 01:23:29.596
Glad to be of service.

01:23:31.230 --> 01:23:32.429
Sir.

01:23:32.431 --> 01:23:34.267
PAMELA: Rachael.
Oh, Rachael.

01:23:38.437 --> 01:23:40.270
PAMELA: Is it true?

01:23:40.272 --> 01:23:41.904
- What?
- You're really leaving?

01:23:41.906 --> 01:23:43.172
CELIA: Won't you miss it?

01:23:43.174 --> 01:23:44.475
PAMELA:
What will she miss?

01:23:44.477 --> 01:23:46.109
- PAMELA: The staff?
- The people.

01:23:46.111 --> 01:23:47.443
Hmm.

01:23:47.445 --> 01:23:50.350
I must say,
I'm surprised at you, Morgan.

01:23:51.350 --> 01:23:52.783
For what?

01:23:52.785 --> 01:23:55.784
I thought you'd prefer
to handle the matter yourself.

01:23:55.786 --> 01:23:57.954
I have no idea
what you're talking about.

01:23:57.956 --> 01:23:59.790
BURNHAM:
Ah, don't play innocent.

01:23:59.792 --> 01:24:01.993
If you're so bloody convinced
Lubert's clean,

